caption: Great food n great people!!!

Amazing food. The flavors linger on your tongue and leave you beyond satisfied. We enjoyed the vegan sampler with tsebhi beghe and were very impressed with the dish. The service was excellent. The experience was authentic. I recommend enjoying a bottle of T'ej wine. It pairs well with the spices. Highly recommended. Will visit again when in the area.
Best Ethiopian in town
Massawa is so good. Great service, lightning and food.
Food was amazing! Been here twice, the service is great. Abraham specifically was very accommodating to our needs, highly recommend!
First time having Ethiopian food. Won't be the last! Family feel and tried a really tasty beer.

This place is the loveliest tastiest and friendliest out there. I studied nearby and would have the same meal maybe 3 or 4 times a week. After some time, they would even recognize my voice when I called to order something. Because of Massawa I discovered a world of new tasty things I didn't even know I liked. It is totally worth it to get out of your way, if necessary, to have a piece of Massawa goodness <3  AND they’re completely vegan friendly
Simply incredible.
Food was delicious! We didn't realize it was Ethiopian when we went- but it was the best surprise- great friendly service!
Beautiful, cozy ambiance with candles and dim lighting. Lots of artistic references to Ethiopia - paintings, pottery, etc. Very friendly staff, and small menu (which is a good thing!)
Food is absolutely amazing! Entire place has a romantic atmosphere.. This is a perfect place for special occasions or if you just want to relax and enjoy good food with your special someone.

Rich Ethiopian cuisine. Packaged for take-out in compartments, with teff separated so it doesn't get soggy on the way home. Friendly service; safe pick-up. We also ate outside there around November(?) on specially built level platforms (sidewalk is sloped) and had an equally enjoyable meal.
THEY FOOD IS AMAZING
Beautiful restaurant, comfortable, clean...plus good service!
Finest Ethiopian food, lovely staff.
Easily the best food in the neighborhood!
I understand why this place been open for over 30 years between The food and the service beyond 5 stars
(Translated by Google) Good food, and a nice bar ..  (Original) Buena comida,y un bonito bar..
The best food ever. Love this place and the service was amazing
A neighborhood gem
Great service.  Food was delicious! No complaints here😊
Amazing experience and very good service
Chatted with Abraham over the phone for a delivery order and everything was flawless. Huge servings, flavorful food, and great customer service! Thank you!!
Was looking at Google maps and saw this place on the map. Ate here 8 years ago and was awed by how great the food was. Plenty spicy and price was not that bad for lunch.
Coming from Kenya, this felt like home. The food was lovely and the servers quite warm.
So so good affordable and excellent service!
Fantastic food...
The food is beyond explanation. Flavorful, beautiful, so so delicious. So many options, especially for vegetarians. The restaurant is very peaceful and calming. Will come here again!
Went for lunch. They had a vegetarian buffet which was really nice. Good amount of food for the price. Nice waitress.
This is the place to talk and then eat

Yummy! I love Ethiopian food and this is better than most of what I've had in Manhattan. I got the Massawa sampler and everything on it was delicious. They choose the side dishes for you, although you can say if you really want something in particular. Glad we did 't dictate, though, because they brought things I wouldn't necessarilly have chosen, but found delicious anyway, particularly the red lentils, which were absolutly incredible. I'm starting to think you can really judge an Ethiopian restaurant by their red lentils. These were excellent!
Delicious food. Great setting. Plenty of options for vegetarians and meat eaters alike.
My son wanted to try Ethiopian.  Delicious.
Very  tasty spicy love spicy food 😍

Pleasant, soothing ambiance; low noise level; food was flawless (and low on spice level); service was flawless too; they sell their spice blend if you'd like to bring it home. I found this place to be better than the other two Ethiopian eateries in midtown.
Love the food! A Lot of veggie options!
Amazing food and ambience.

The decor was quite nice, warm, and cozy, and the food was very good (although know that you will eat with your hands). The only problem is that everything is well overpriced (as is commensurate with the neighborhood in which the restaurant is situated). I ate at a similar restaurant in a less expensive neighborhood; the food/service was just as good but the meals were half to three-quarters the cost. I will admit cost should be a variable judged extraneous to quality, but $8 for a bottled beer? Yes, I'm from out of town; I assume New Yorkers in Manhattan are use to being price-gouged.
Great vibe and big shareable platters
Beautiful new room. Old favorite renewed impressively.
Great place for Ethiopian food near Columbia University.
Phenomenal food, friendly folks and a relaxed ambience.
(Translated by Google) Good service but I didn't like the food much.  (Original) Buen servicio pero no me gustó mucho la comida.

Excellent food, excellent service. I wanted to try the Tej (honey wine) and the server suggested that I might want a taste first - and she was right, it was a good novelty but the South African cab was a better fit for the dinner.
Great flavors and a fun place to eat

Ethiopian food is not too common in the United States, far from it, but if you want to try some, go no further than Massawa. They have many Ethiopian dishes and it feels real authentic. The food was absolutely delicious and the presentation fantastic. This is tasty exotic food that you eat in a sort of bread, flavorful and delicious. I loved it.

Renovated and more spacious than before. Pleasant atmosphere, with a more Ethiopian inspired decor than in the past, this is definitely a restaurant in which you will want to dine.  Portion size is reasonable and the spices are savory.

I do not understand why people are so excite about this place. I came in around 4:15 pm to meet with a good friend of mine. Before a server took our order she sat down at a table next to us to have her lunch break or something. There was no one else on the floor, so I kept looking at her. She continued to chew her food and looked back at me. We sat at our table with menu open for about another 15 minutes watching the server having her lunch. Then another girl finally came up to us and took the order. I had an appetizer sampler platter for one - not worth ordering. The description in the menus sounds so much more delicious then the actual dishes are. Their famous special coffe is only served until early afternoon. I’m giving two stars for the vibe. It was cozy and quite. I will definitely not be coming back.
Perfect ambiance for date night, time alone, or a gathering. The oldest African restaurant in New York best place to experience history. Service is superb

Delicious food. Can be served individually or, more traditionally, spread out in portions on the injera, their wonderfully sour flatbread. Like in a Chinese restaurant, you can eat whatever you want, however much you want. Or, you can leave whatever you don’t want. There is some spice heat but not a great deal. The servers are very helpful in making suggestions. You eat with your fingers usually. And you can still take home leftovers.
Incredible service and amazing ambience. I really like the renovations they made. The food is delicious!

Best and first Eritrean resturant in NY (also serves some Ethiopian dishes), finally finished it’s expansion and the resturant looks amazing. I’m a regular here and bring all friends & family to enjoy the cuisine, culture and can’t forget the Honey wine.👌🏼
Hands down the best Ethiopian food in NYC.
Love the food. My favorite place to go
It looks good but tastes not. My friend and I won't come here again.
Great food and the lady who served us was extremely hospitable
Tasty and fairly quick eats.  Good for a workday lunch, study break or dinner.
Great food, great staff. Authentic Eritrean and Ethiopian restaurant
This place is NOT OPEN WASTED A TRIP TO FIND IT CLOSED VERY ANNOYING
Still not open, but construction is ongoing.
This place is so over rated and over priced. if you are looking for a typical Ethiopian food this is not the place to go. What a Joke!
I don't actually want to rate this place but as of this date it is apparently under renovation and not open.
The food is fantastic and the staff is friendly.
Good, old Eritrean restaurant.

Absolutely the best restaurant in the area. Authentic Ethiopian and Eritrean cuisine. Inexpensive. Columbia students and faculty friendly. Discounted prices for lunch. Take reservations ahead of time. Large crowd friendly. Decent wine collection. Best African coffee in this area.
Love this Ethiopian restaurant which offers a satiating experience for my love for Injara. A must visit in the beautiful Harlem neighbourhood.
Renovating
My favorite restaurant for Eritrean and Ethiopian food. Excellent customer service and delicious, quickly prepared dishes. Never over crowded when I go, either.

We thoroughly enjoyed a wonderful Ethiopian meal here. Even the wine and beer list were a pleasant surprise, with selections from Ethiopia and South Africa that were delightful. Some of the dishes were a little spicier than I usually tolerate, but so delicious that I could not stop eating them. Wonderful service, ambiance and food.
Food taste and Presentation was outstanding.Overall everything tasted amazing.Thank You!!

The food is good when you have the munchies. Nice staff, except for the one who started having such an attitude to me, after a stranger bought me a drink there. I don't go in anymore, as there are other places with a non-rude vibe.

Cozy restaurant near Columbia university. Good dishes and flavours (the meat is just a bit sweeter than what I'm used to), but unfortunately portions are not very abundant, compared to the price. Very kind service!
Fine Ethiopian food with a very attentive staff.
our favorite family restaurant
Great food and friendly staff makes this eatery a neighborhood favorite!
Delicious Ethiopian restaurant
One of the best places in New York City...If you are in the city and a foodie, you should dine at this awesome family owned restaurant.
Great service, great food.
First time eating Ethiopian food.  The injera bread was filling.  They look like crepes.  The chicken cubes had jalapenos which made them kind of spicy, but still good
Nice place to be in.
Good food don't expect much from the beer selection. St George Amber your best bet
Great staff, nice settings but poor food. Grew up in Addis Abeba so was very disappointed with tasteless injera and various dishes ...
Cozy and friendly dining atmosphere. Always  satisfied with the food and service.

Ethiopian food is by it's very nature flavorful and Massawa doesn't disappoint. The causal atmosphere coupled with the friendly service just enhance the experience. Massawa is hands down my favorite Ethiopian spot in NYC.

The food was in general pretty uninspired- some were tasty, others very bland. The fava bean dip was in the former category, the veggies that came with the main dish were as bland as could be. Friendly service, good vibes.
Food was okay
Fabulous!
Delicious food and amazing service!! Will definitely be returning and bringing friends!

This is a wonderful  little place! We loved the food here! The special shiro is a must try! The hostess was really nice and helpful. Their bar with a soccer world cup replica will be a nice place to watch the upcoming soccer world cup! Also their selection of African beers was pretty good. I'd recommend trying tusker, nice mild lager that goes well with the food!
Good food, good wine list.
Delicious. I'll come back.
Delicious.  My nephew suggested it.  Said he loves it.  So we loved it as well. Great service, music and food.

Small, simple and smooth spot. I can't believe that I have been in this area a few times without taking note of this beauty.  Lots of choices when it comes to alcoholic beverages from Ethiopia (I can't stand it when I go to a restaurant representing a country without any drinks from there.) Beer, wine,  you name it I was impressed!  The prices were affordable, this is a good spot to bring a date if you leave nearby and you can also do groups of about 10 if I'm not mistaken.  Staff also deserve serious praise. You feel welcome as soon as you step in.
The food is amazing and the people are kind and friendly. This is one of my favorite restaurants in NYC!
Massawa is an authentic Ethiopian restaurant in the heart of Manhattan, New York. For you who never try any African food, I fully recommend this. :)
Do not miss this! The food is fantastic and the service wonderful.

Real simple decor with fantastic Ethiopian fare. I love really getting connected with my food and there’s no better way to do it than to dig in with your fingers. Great for groups and food sharing. Definitely the kind of food that brings people together.
Good food. It's a family owned restaurant and everyone in there is great.
I love this place! Tasty dishes and friendly staff. Definitely worth a visit, especially if you've never tried ethipian before.

Love this restaurant! I usually have chicken tebsi or beef zegini, so my food experience from there is mostly based on these two dishes. The food is unbelievably tasty. Every bite is like “wow”. I often order for pickup and portions are really generous.  The interior of the restaurant is not fancy, but nice - imagine a place where college professors go for lunch, that would be the right description.  The only thing that I don’t like about this place is that they don’t deliver. I work 10 minutes walk from there and when I called once to order for delivery, the lady on the phone said they have to charge me $25 to deliver $13 lunch special meal. The guy that works there is very nice, so maybe had he answered the phone he would have been more accommodating. I never tried calling for delivery again.
Their food is so good.
Great food, nice and spicy Berbere Lamb dish!
Delicious food.
Great food and super fast for lunch because I was on a time crunch...service was on point and friendly...and the tea selection was good...I could of used just a bit more ginger lol...
My absolute favorite restaurant in New York City ...truly delicious Ethiopian food within a lovely atmosphere and prompt service.

(Translated by Google) The friendly waiter, the little brother, poured hot water, the dough was sour, and the dry mouth could not swallow, but the sauce-flavored beef did a good job, and the beef and the sauce were barely able to eat the noodles. The beef is really fragrant, and the dough with the butter is very fragrant.  (Original) 亲切的服务员小哥给倒热水，面皮是酸的，干口无法下咽，但是酱香牛肉做的不错，就着牛肉和酱料吃勉强能吃面皮。牛肉真的很香，沾上了牛油的面皮变得挺香。

Three of us ordered two entrees and were thrilled -- and filled -- by a beautifully presented platter of delicious food as carefully presented as what you might find at a sushi restaurant.  I would add a star if I could for the service -- so warm, welcoming, and helpful that I felt like a regular from the second we arrived.  This place is a gem.
Amazing authentic food with great service. A must try!
Great food at a small corner restaurant.
Their veggie Timtimo (spicy red lentils) was delicious! And very friendly service.

We ordered a family style platter with spicy chicken, lamb, pumpkin, lentil, chickpea, and stewed cabbage. It was amazing. The waiter was super friendly and even have us a complimentary dessert. We'll be back soon!
Favorite restaurant. Their ingredients are fresh and delicious. Service is wonderful. An awesome experience to eat there

Massawa catered a business lunch for my company. All the food was delicious, at appropriate temperature, and interesting. The chopped beef was tender and flavorful. Their injera bread is quality as well.
delicious. you will not regret it. and feels great to be a tiny part in keeping this popular, one of the longest standing restaurants in the area open!
Fantastic food, great local ambience, amazing value. Friendly, wonderful service. Just one of the best restaurants I've ever been to.
Very decent Ethiopian food. Quick service and great vibe
Delicious food but expensive. Definitely try their beer.

You'll want to call it Eat-thiopian
Delicious food and Kim will take care of you!!!!
Tasty food! Moderate cost! Great service, indeed very helpful staff. I love their veggie/vegan platter
The food is mediocre but quite pricy. I would go there if I was dying for some Ethiopian food. Sheba on 42nd street is much better one.
Excellent Ethiopian/Eritrean food. Everything was made to perfection. Truly a unique experience.
I've tried most of the Ethiopian restaurants in Manhattan, and a few in the other boroughs, but Massawa is the one I keep coming back to.
Sorry, it didnt wotk for me: beef was too hard and service so so...

For some reason when I went to this place I thought I was going to an Indian restaurant. Imagine the waiter's look when I asked her if they had lassie. She went from slightly amused to panic while politely explaining to me that was a drink you'd get at on Indian restaurant, not on an Ethiopian restaurant. Food choice was varied enough to allow you to pick your favourite but not to extent to the point that you end up 10 minutes just to figure out what to eat. Being an Ethiopian restaurant when the food arrived there was no cutlery. You eat by picking up discs of very thin flat brand and using it to pick up your food. Everything is served on a giant platter from where you and all the people in your party will eat. It was great fun! I was on a business trip and having lunch with a customer, it was a great way to break the ice and we all ended up having a laugh and dropping most of the useless formalities.  The food was delicious! And being served of the same platter I got to try several different dishes. It was quite filling as well. Not too spicy but definitely not bland, everything cooked to perfect tenderness.  This is a great place for casual lunch or dinner, especially if you bring some friends (or acquaintances) with you.  Service was fast and very pleasant.

This place has the essentially the same menu as every other Ethiopian restaurant in the US and Canada that I've visited. The food is prepared well,  served well, and the atmosphere is quiet. See the menus that I posted.
It's a very good and tasty spot to go grab some amazing Ethiopian food. Not to mention the waitresses are stunning😉
Food is great but I have had better Ethipion food right here in the Triangle!
Quiet, great service, and delicious food. The prices are high though.
This little Ethiopian restaurant is a treasure.
Voicemail seems to always be full and rarely an answer..

The food at Massawa is okay. If you've never has Ethiopian before and you want to try it out this may be the place for you. The flavors are very mild bordering on bland. It's not bad it just isn't great Ethiopian food.

My favorite place for Ethiopian food in the city. Everything is so good here! My favorite is the lamb tibs and the okra dish they make. Great lunch deala. Just make sure you're prepared to come out smelling of spices when you leave the restaurant -- maybe don't make any fancy or sexy plans after dinner here. ;)

I don't know much about Ethiopian food, but I really like this place. The food looks good and it tastes even better. I have been to another Ethiopian place before and the food here is better. I would give it 5 stars if the bread was hot and if they gave customers hot towels to clean your hand.

Portions are atypically small for this type of cuisine. Food is lightly/barely spiced. Approaching bland. Wait staff not very attentive (especially near end of meal). Great to experience once, but certainly not a favorite. 1st and last visit. I'll look for another Ethiopian restaurant.

Terrible. I went there with a group of friends – waiters didn’t help at all in the selection and were not friendly. We didn’t get half of the food we ordered and got charged for all of it. Extra drinks were listed on the bill (around $50 value) – WATCH OUT! Not even an apologize for the “mistake”…
Standard Ethiopian food with a nice dining area
One of the most overpriced restaurants!
I never seen like this east African restaurant the worst poor service and the food is very bad!
A decent restaurant. But one of the best in the neighborhood.
The service is excellent and the environment is warm and welcoming
Excellent food
Solid, affordable lunch choice in Morningside for Ethiopian food. Great for vegans-- the veggie platter is delicious.
Solid food, friendly staff, cozy ambience. I'd recommend trying a few different things with a friend or two.

Quiet Ethiopian restaurant in Morningside Heights. Food is really good and served in the traditional Ethiopian style (no utensils). If you go in a group they'll serve it on huge platters with everything you ordered spread out, so it's a lot of fun to with four or more people. It's a little on the expensive side, but really good.
Really good establishment, highly recommend for authentic Eritrean & Ethiopian cuisine.
When you need a place to bring friends, this place is it.
Go here for the novelty of eating with your hands from a communal plate, but not for the taste of the food, which is very mediocre.
The waitress was very disrespectful! The place was baking hot and we asked her if they had ac.. she replied if you dont like it, leave!

Amazing food at an affordable price. I've had both the lamb and beef dishes here, and they are both fantastic. The bread as some have mentioned has an odd taste, but it seems to compliment the food when eaten together. They know what they are doing.
I like Eritrean and Ethiopian food . The best restaurant ever I got serving this countries food is "Massawa Restaurant." Thanks Massawa Restaurant.
Nice stewed beef. However the shrimp and chicken is over-cooked, portion of food is relatively small and pastry tastes weird.
(Translated by Google) The cake is sour, the texture is very good.  (Original) 饼好酸 质感挺好哈哈
The food (Injera, with different choices of side dishes) was good. The service was fine.  But the place was a little to dimly lit for my taste.

Trekked out here for dinner from the outer boroughs, after having pleasant memories of good food and good service when my husband and I lived here more than 10 years ago... it was a busy Saturday night when we arrived, but we were seated promptly, with menus and water.  Waitress came over, and asked, "Ready to order?" And I told her we wanted the Veggie Combo and Meat Combo to share.  She looked at me, nodded her head, said "ok" and took the menus.  We waited 1/2 hour... I asked her to check on our order.  She said she would.  15 minutes later, she came over and asked if we had ordered already?!? I said yes, we had, right after we walked in.  She claimed that she had asked me, in the beginning, right before she collected the menus, "Have you already ordered?" when she had said (and I had heard) no such thing.  My husband and I got up and left, having to return to Queens with empty stomachs, since we only had the babysitter for another hour and had other family obligations that we could not be late for.  What kind of system (table service-kitchen coordination) does a long-time restaurant have, that they could mess this up so badly? I hope this never happens again.

Delicious food. Very flavorful and well executed. And price is great too for NYC. I only have concerns with service that was slow (but polite and nice), dessert list (no Ethiopian item, wtw) and coffee, no Ethiopian coffee, come on man ...
Amazing Everytime I go
BEST Ethiopian food in NYC. OK service-- awesome food. Great prices and portions.  Thanks for being consistent and delish!

I woke up at 9pm on my first day in NYC, still feeling sad and angry on my failing to take the Schengen visa interview in France embassy this morning due to the damned shortline bus company which oversold tickets. After searching yelp, I decided to go to this Ethiopian restaurant instead of getting a burger at Flat Top, 5 Napkin or Shake Shack.  Something new.  Nice ambiance with its music, decoration, dim candle, wine and water glasses and heavy wooden tables & chairs. Exotic food. This was the first time I tried African cuisine. I ordered Massawa Combo. It was a five-dishes combo served on a piece of injera, with two extra injera folded. Chicken w/ tomato, Beef, Lamb steak, Beans, Lettuce. Injera is a white Ethiopian flatbread, similar to a crepe, very soft, spongy. It is *very* sour, because, according to wiki, the deff dough fermented for several days with sourdough starter. VERY SOUR. The dishes were great, especially beef and lamb.  24 dollars, tax & tips included. Worth a try.
Good place to grab Ethiopian.

I love Ethiopian food and I've tried the different offerings in NYC.  Hands down, Massawa is my go to Ethiopian spot.  It's conveniently located next to Columbia University on Amsterdam Avenue.  The food is awesome!  My favorite items here:  Honey Wine (you have to start the meal with a glass of this sweet white wine), beef sambusa (but place 2 orders because if you're hungry this will just get you yearning for more Ethiopian food), Alitcha Beghe (a lamb dish with a slight spicy taste) and injera which is served with every meal.  I'm drooling just thinking about this.  Must go soon! My son (4 years old) loves the food too.  Particularly the vegetarian options:  collard greens, shiro (ground chick peas) and Alitcha (potatoes) are so tasty.  Great place if you're vegan or vegetarian.

Decently good food, but the main problem was the service. The waitress was nice but very spacey. We had to ask for more water and we received and finished our entrée before our appetizer came out. We finally asked for them to cancel our order since they kept telling us the appetizer was "being made" when we had already finished dinner 15 minutes earlier. Glad to have different option for dinner but the staff need to get it together
Absolutely delicious food, excellent service, reasonable prices.  I strongly recommend Massawa Restaurant.
Although it's not much to look at, I enjoyed the food - lots of taste and felt authentic. Service could be faster but not a big deal.  Well be returning soon!

Watch out for the SCAM: Five of us went to dine, and the waitress asked if we want to share. By "sharing", she meant instead of each person gets the dish ordered along with the accompanying, we only got two full plates!! Instead of each person has a large tray of food, five of us only had two plates. And they charge way too much for extra bread!Bottom line: WAY over priced, and deceptive practice by the waitress. Stay away, if not, when asked whether or not want to share, please say "NO"!  They automatically charge you 18% tip in your bill, so be aware!
nice meat and bread
Very good, though the menu selection is limited compared to other Ethiopian restaurants.
delicious ethiopian food. worth a detour
